                <a href="./viewtopic.php?p=4715783&amp;sid=8243344a41cf6dc9193566b78ba0e612#p4715783">Posted: Wed Sep 19, 2007 11:01 pm</a>
              </div>
              <div class="post-actions">
                
              </div>
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              I don't know if saying science got us to the moon and so forth is quite accurate.  Those achievements, while remarkable, are technological.  Science and technology are different things.  Related, but different.  I suppose for a little kid needing his or her mind expanded, the distinction may be lost. <BR><BR>I suggest emphasizing that the <I>knowledge</I> we gain through science, like figuring out how gravity works, gives engineers and inventors what they need to go forward, like the way one needs to understand gravity to get an Apollo capsuel into orbit around the moon.<BR><BR>I only make the distinction because when this kid grows up to be a congressman, I want him or her to vote for funding the NSF and basic research because just discovering something is worthwhile.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
