          <td class="post-date-actions">
            <div class="post-date-actions-inner">
              <div class="post-actions">
                
              </div>
              <div class="post-date">
                <a href="./viewtopic.php?p=4715779&amp;sid=8243344a41cf6dc9193566b78ba0e612#p4715779">Posted: Thu Sep 20, 2007 7:30 am</a>
              </div>
              <div class="post-actions">
                
              </div>
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content">Originally posted by willbb:<BR><BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content">Originally posted by 1up:<BR>That kid should experience the joy of titrations </div></BLOCKQUOTE><BR>There is no joy in titrations.<BR> </div></BLOCKQUOTE>I resemble that statement! My first job after college consisted of nothing more than titrations and viscosity measurements.<BR><BR>So, I have some experience in this area. When I was in high school, my chemistry teacher used to take a group of us around the state to do science shows for middle school kids. Now, I'm a freshman chem and freshmen bio TA during the academic year, and participate in a science "camp" for high school kids during the summers. Here are a few methods that I've found work quite well:<BR><BR>For very young children, ask them why the sky is blue. If they are creatively inclined, they will likely generate some fantastical explanation. Then ask them how they can be sure they are correct. This will likely discourage the child. So then you promise them that there are ways to figure out if they are correct or not. It's called science. The prospect of retaining a mastery of knowledge of the world is very tempting to a child, especially when they are at the tail end of the "cocoon" stage and beginning to realize just how big and vast and complex the world really is.<BR><BR>For slightly older children, say 4th to 8th grade, demonstrations really are the best bet. However, it is important that the demonstration teach as well as excite. How many times have you seen the whole coke and mentos thing? So how does it really work? You see, not revealing the science behind an exciting explosion may actually turn a student off from science. Here's a few that I really like:<BR><BR>For explosions, don't just light off some hydrogen. For one thing, the boom ain't that big. What you do is take a 2 liter soda bottle and cut off the bottom to create a bell container. Put a cork with a hole in it in the top, and place a glass tube through the hole. Then you hook up either a hydrogen cylinder or a hydrogen generator (HCl/Muriatic acid and zinc/galvanized bolts work well) with a rubber tube. Give the container time to completely fill with hydrogen, then remove the rubber tube. Hold a match or lighter above the glass tube sticking out from the cork. This is where it gets fun. A student that understands some basics of hydrogen will expect a boom. There won't be one. Instead, you'll get a small flame (the flame may, in fact, be invisible, but it's there). The flame will burn until enough oxygen from the air has mixed with the hydrogen, escaping from the top, and then...well, let's just say that a ballon full of hydrogen doesn't even compare! Explain stoichiometry and chemical equations: 2 parts H2 for every 1 part O2.<BR><BR>Another that's quite simple is to tie a bowling ball to the ceiling (or someplace equally high). Then you grab a volunteer from the audience, and blind-fold them. Stand them off to one side of an open area, a good 10-15 feet from where the bowling ball is hanging. Then, pull the bowling ball back until it's only a centimeter or so from the volunteer's nose, and release. Wait for the gasps as the bowling ball swings away, then back, and stops only a few centimeters from the volunteer's nose. Note that it's important the volunteer be blind-folded so they don't inadvertently lean forward and get smacked in the face! Explain about conservation of energy.<BR><BR>As students get a bit older, you can start broaching some more advanced topics. A fun one, if you have access to liquid nitrogen, is to place a bouncy ball into liquid nitrogen. When you take the ball out and let it drop...it shatters! If the students have learned about atoms and molecules, you can explain how they move around inside a substance, and cooling them makes everything more rigid.<BR><BR>Finally, for high school students, if they're not already inclined toward science, there's less that can be done. Even if they are inclined toward science, much of the college experience can serve to discourage them to pursue this path to it's completion. One thing I've found is that very few high school students really understand how scientific research works. They understand science, but <I>doing</I> science is something else entirely.<BR><BR>So, what I've been doing with these students is showing them a standard luciferase reaction. Mix A, B, C, and D...and it glows! That's exciting...and that's all I do. I usually prepend this with a brief lecture on the scientific method, and once the reaction is finished I'll say, "Ok, you've made an observation, now go be scientists!" Of course, you have to expend a good deal of effort overseeing everything they do, and it helps to stop periodically and see how far they've strayed from the scientific method. I also like to throw in short lectures on the value of controls, the need for discrete measurements, and the value of collaboration. Overall, some students will end up being very bored. These are not the students that will be pursuing science. The vast majority, though, have always found the freedom to investigate anything, along with the required discipline to actually achieve something, exciting. Most of my students have left even more excited by a career in science then when they came.<BR><BR>Really, what it comes down to is presenting science as it is: possibilities, endless possibilities.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
