              <BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content">Originally posted by FreeRadical*:<BR>The science of teaching science is based on cognitive theories.   <A HREF="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean_Piaget" TARGET=_blank>Piaget's</A> work plays an important role in some science teacher training.  Flashy demonstration and experiments can motivate students to learn, however, science does require discipline.  Students still have to learn how to do the boring parts like crunching numbers and estimating errors.  <BR><BR>The last two stages of development in Piaget's theories are Concrete Operational and Formal Operational.  The change from concrete to formal is marked by the ability to think abstractly and logically.  These are the two stages that best describe middle and high school students thought processes.<BR><BR>That's all I'll add for now as I am sleepy.  <img src="http://episteme.arstechnica.com/groupee_common/emoticons/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" width="15" height="15"><!--graemlin::)--> </div></BLOCKQUOTE>Yes of course you have to consider the student's level of cognitive development, but this question is more of a "how can I motivate someone" thing.

              

              
              
