              <BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content">Originally posted by .milFox:<BR><BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content">Originally posted by Dunni:<BR><BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content">Originally posted by Donlo:<BR>I would demonstrate something in a bill the science guy kind of way like lighting ants on fire or something </div></BLOCKQUOTE><BR><BR>Explosions.<BR>Everyone likes to see things go BOOM! </div></BLOCKQUOTE><BR><BR>=) </div></BLOCKQUOTE>++.  Our chem teacher (must be something about chemistry, given andyfatbastard's post) showed us how very fine powders can be an explosion hazard by blowing the lid off a syrup can using nothing more than a match, some custard powder and a good, hard puff on the end of a tube.  And I learned how to make TNT <img src="http://episteme.arstechnica.com/groupee_common/emoticons/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" width="15" height="15"><!--graemlin::)--><BR><BR>Ian Smith (my science and chem teacher for almost my entire HS career), I salute you!

              

              
              
