              <BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content">Originally posted by FreeRadical*:<BR>The science of teaching science is based on cognitive theories.   <A HREF="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean_Piaget" TARGET=_blank>Piaget's</A> work plays an important role in some science teacher training.  Flashy demonstration and experiments can motivate students to learn, however, science does require discipline.  Students still have to learn how to do the boring parts like crunching numbers and estimating errors.  leepy.  <img src="http://episteme.arstechnica.com/groupee_common/emoticons/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" width="15" height="15"><!--graemlin::)--> </div></BLOCKQUOTE> Data analysis is fun; that's where it all comes together.  Computers have taken out most of the pure number-crunching routine.

              

              
              
