              <BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content">Originally posted by flyingember:<BR>If a little kid says "Science sucks!" what would be your example of cool science? </div></BLOCKQUOTE><BR><BR>How little are we talking about? <BR><BR>In our 2nd grade class, we're studying the life of insects. Bugs are always cool if you can see them grow in stages. So far, each kiddo has a mealworm that has begun its metamorphosis. A bunch of kids shouting "PUPAE!" and giggling like baby loons is a wonderful thing. It appears that Mika has inherited her Dad's penchant for silliness and mischief.   <img src="http://episteme.arstechnica.com/groupee_common/emoticons/icon_wink.gif" alt="Wink" width="15" height="15"><!--graemlin:;)--> <BR><BR>In Kindergarten, they are studying machines, and the "final" project for the class is to build a robot. Never mind that they don't actually work, they begin the process by taking machines apart to "demystify" them, then they get to take all of the parts, assign a function to them and assemble the parts into a robot of their choosing. They come up with some pretty creative robots. But, I have to admit, a bunch of 5 year olds with a pile of electronics and some wire cutters is a scary sight. I've already had to warn Jaeden to NOT do to Daddy's computer what he did to the Tascam 112 that he took apart in class.   <img src="http://episteme.arstechnica.com/groupee_common/emoticons/icon_biggrin.gif" alt="Big Green" width="15" height="15"><!--graemlin::bigdumbgrin:--> <BR><BR>Kids at that age are very tactile, as it's part of their natural discovery process. Anything "hands on" is bound to engage wee ones, anything "lecture based" and too abstract, you lose them to nap time.<BR><BR>EDIT: This Forum really needs to be on the main navigation (when you click on the little "house" icon). I would have never known about it if it weren't linked up in The Lounge.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
